    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p>Never published before this edition.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="0"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="line"/><certainty locus="name" match=".."/>
                    <lb n="1"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="line"/><gap reason="illegible" quantity="1" unit="character"/><gap reason="lost" quantity="2" unit="character"/>
                    <lb n="2"/><w lemma="δεκάτα"><supplied reason="lost">δεκά</supplied>ταν</w>
                </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
               </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> au titre de la dîme.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> as a tithe.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> come decima.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="ar">
            <p/>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
             <p>Although we lack information about the findspot and in spite of the lacunar condition of the stone, it belongs evidently to the bulk of dedications of the tithe to Apollo. We 
             cannot know whether the formulation was the most implicit one, without verb and name of the divinity, or a more expanded one.</p>
            </div></body>
    </text>
